# ~/.zshrc.local — machine-specific overrides
#
# This file is gitignored. Copy this example to ~/.zshrc.local and edit
# with your own values. It is sourced from ~/.zshrc at the very end, so
# anything here overrides values set earlier.
#
# Use this file for:
#   - Aliases pointing to private repos (paths that shouldn't be public)
#   - Machine-specific PATH additions
#   - Personal API keys / tokens (or, better, source them from a separate file)
#   - Identity strings (real name, email) you don't want in a public repo

# ─── Private tool paths ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Example: alias pointing into a private scripts
# alias private-script="$HOME/path/to/your/private-script.sh"

# ─── Machine-specific PATH ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Add anything that lives outside the standard /usr/local/bin, ~/.local/bin, etc.
# export PATH="$PATH:/opt/some-vendor-tool/bin"
# export PATH="$PATH:$HOME/Tools/custom-binaries"

# ─── Engagement directory override ─────────────────────────────────────────
# By default, new_engagement creates dirs under ~/Engagements.
# Override here if you keep them somewhere else on this machine.
# export ENGAGEMENTS_DIR="$HOME/Work/Engagements"

# ─── Private functions / aliases ───────────────────────────────────────────
# Anything you don't want in a public dotfiles repo goes here.
# alias vpn-up="sudo openvpn --config $HOME/.vpn/client.ovpn"

# ─── Secrets (consider a separate file) ────────────────────────────────────
# If you have API keys or tokens, prefer sourcing them from an even more
# protected file (chmod 600) rather than putting them inline:
# [[ -f ~/.secrets ]] && source ~/.secrets